1
00:00:47,661 --> 00:00:49,219
Travel is useful,
it exercises the imagination.

2
00:00:49,341 --> 00:00:51,297
All the rest
is disappointment and fatigue.

3
00:00:51,421 --> 00:00:54,060
Our journey is entirely imaginary.
That is its strength.

4
00:00:54,181 --> 00:00:55,933
lt goes from life to death.

5
00:00:56,061 --> 00:00:58,336
People, animals, cities, things,
all are imagined.

6
00:00:58,461 --> 00:00:59,780
lt's a novel,
just a fictitious narrative.

7
00:00:59,901 --> 00:01:02,620
Littre says so, and he's never wrong.
And besides, anyone can do as much.

8
00:01:02,741 --> 00:01:05,574
You just have to close your eyes.
lt's on the other side of life.

9
00:01:05,701 --> 00:01:07,851
Louis-Ferdinand Celine
Journey to the End of the Night

10
00:01:12,021 --> 00:01:13,454
Fire!

11
00:02:35,421 --> 00:02:37,173
You're a real pain in the ass!

12
00:04:37,981 --> 00:04:39,334
Enough!

13
00:04:39,461 --> 00:04:42,294
They even have cocktails
with cherries. Remember?

14
00:04:42,421 --> 00:04:44,776
Hey, jerks!

15
00:04:45,101 --> 00:04:46,454
l'll screw you!

16
00:04:47,821 --> 00:04:48,890
l'll screw you!

17
00:05:06,621 --> 00:05:08,418
Have you seen Ermanno?

18
00:06:02,181 --> 00:06:05,491
- l'll screw you! Now!
- Get lost!

19
00:06:41,501 --> 00:06:42,490
What the hell are you doing?

20
00:07:15,421 --> 00:07:17,173
My phone's been stolen!

21
00:08:01,221 --> 00:08:03,291
l'm starring in two TV dramas...

22
00:08:03,501 --> 00:08:05,457
l'm playing a Pope in one,

23
00:08:05,621 --> 00:08:08,693
and a junkie on the road to recovery
in the other.

24
00:08:08,821 --> 00:08:12,530
lmpressive!
No theatre work?

25
00:08:12,661 --> 00:08:15,733
l'm supposed to do
Shakespeare with Pietro, but...

26
00:08:15,941 --> 00:08:17,897
it has to be at least
three hours long,

27
00:08:18,061 --> 00:08:22,691
be an ambitious project,
and no more small cities!

28
00:08:23,021 --> 00:08:26,855
l'm trying to write a piece
for theatre, and the concept is...

29
00:08:26,981 --> 00:08:30,940
- What about you?
- l might give up acting.

30
00:08:31,101 --> 00:08:34,332
ln this shitty country there are
never any good female roles.

31
00:08:34,501 --> 00:08:37,459
l'll write my first novel,
a Proust-style piece.

32
00:08:37,581 --> 00:08:40,254
Really?
Proust is my favourite writer!

33
00:08:40,381 --> 00:08:42,497
Along with Ammaniti...

34
00:08:43,421 --> 00:08:44,900
What a coincidence.

35
00:08:52,581 --> 00:08:54,014
Who is that woman?

36
00:08:54,181 --> 00:08:56,217
Don't you recognise her?
lt's Lorena.

37
00:08:56,541 --> 00:08:57,735
Who?

38
00:08:57,861 --> 00:09:01,934
An ex TV showgirl, now in
full physical and mental decline.

39
00:09:02,061 --> 00:09:06,100
Never seen her! But then
l've never had a television.

40
00:09:06,221 --> 00:09:10,692
Viola, l know you don't have one.
You tell me all the time.

41
00:09:10,861 --> 00:09:13,500
- What does she do now?
- Nothing, of course.

42
00:09:15,461 --> 00:09:16,974
Happy birthday, Jep!

43
00:09:17,141 --> 00:09:19,291
Happy birthday, Rome!

44
00:10:03,301 --> 00:10:06,020
La Colita!

45
00:11:25,181 --> 00:11:28,378
To this question, as kids,

46
00:11:28,501 --> 00:11:31,857
my friends always gave
the same answer...

47
00:11:32,341 --> 00:11:34,093
"pussy".

48
00:11:34,621 --> 00:11:36,339
Whereas l answered...

49
00:11:36,941 --> 00:11:39,250
"the smell of old
people's houses".

50
00:11:39,981 --> 00:11:41,653
The question was:

51
00:11:41,781 --> 00:11:46,332
"What do you like most, really,
in life?"

52
00:11:47,341 --> 00:11:50,492
l was destined for sensibility.

53
00:11:51,141 --> 00:11:54,656
l was destined to become a writer.

54
00:11:55,101 --> 00:12:00,016
l was destined to become
Jep Gambardella.

55
00:12:09,621 --> 00:12:11,737
You paid no attention
to me tonight!

56
00:12:11,941 --> 00:12:15,490
Romano, don't start moaning,
we're not an item.

57
00:12:16,061 --> 00:12:18,655
- You liked that guy?
- l like everyone and no one.

58
00:12:18,781 --> 00:12:21,659
But l wonder why you're always
with me when it's no one's turn.

59
00:12:21,781 --> 00:12:25,456
- Will you take me to the airport?
- Sure. What time are you leaving?

60
00:12:26,941 --> 00:12:28,738
- ln three hours.
- Three hours?

61
00:12:30,341 --> 00:12:33,014
Then l should crash on your sofa...

62
00:12:33,141 --> 00:12:37,373
Go home, l need to pack
and l don't want anyone around.

63
00:12:37,501 --> 00:12:40,413
- But l live miles away.
- See you at 8:00.

64
00:12:47,581 --> 00:12:49,412
Goodnight.

65
00:13:02,541 --> 00:13:04,418
Guys?

66
00:13:20,981 --> 00:13:22,858
Guys?

67
00:13:38,941 --> 00:13:40,454
Children!

68
00:14:08,141 --> 00:14:09,654
Run along!

69
00:15:07,461 --> 00:15:09,133
Catellani?

70
00:15:11,181 --> 00:15:12,660
The best, of course.

71
00:15:14,981 --> 00:15:18,337
Did Catellani the tailor
make your suit?

72
00:16:08,181 --> 00:16:11,059
There was no doubt
about Malagna's shady intentions.

73
00:16:11,181 --> 00:16:15,652
The girl should be rescued
at any cost, without loss of time.

74
00:16:16,381 --> 00:16:17,814
Sir, you drank!

75
00:16:17,941 --> 00:16:20,057
Just enough to forget
my birthday.

76
00:16:20,701 --> 00:16:22,976
- You want infusion?
- Heavens, no!

77
00:16:25,501 --> 00:16:27,093
- l got you a present.
- How sweet!

78
00:16:27,221 --> 00:16:29,940
This is a lucky charm
from my country.

79
00:16:32,421 --> 00:16:35,618
Good thing it's lucky,
because it's pretty ugly.

80
00:16:35,741 --> 00:16:38,460
Keep it on your bedside
and stop complaining!

81
00:16:38,661 --> 00:16:42,336
l will! And thanks.
Wake me up at 15:00, you rascal.

82
00:16:43,301 --> 00:16:45,212
You're funny when you call me that!

83
00:20:01,421 --> 00:20:03,616
l don't love you!

84
00:20:07,301 --> 00:20:09,019
Brilliant!

85
00:20:17,941 --> 00:20:19,135
Did you enjoy the performance?

86
00:20:22,061 --> 00:20:23,779
Parts of it.

87
00:20:23,901 --> 00:20:26,415
That violent head-butt
made me understand many things.

88
00:20:26,541 --> 00:20:28,497
- Let's start from the beginning.
- Or the end?

89
00:20:29,181 --> 00:20:31,376
You know, Talia Concept
loves to provoke.

90
00:20:31,541 --> 00:20:35,011
Don't bother, there are more
important things than provoking me.

91
00:20:35,181 --> 00:20:38,856
And this habit of speaking
in the third person is unbearable.

92
00:20:39,021 --> 00:20:40,374
What are you reading?

93
00:20:40,541 --> 00:20:43,897
l don't need to read, l live
on vibrations, extra-sensory ones.

94
00:20:44,021 --> 00:20:49,971
Extra-sensoriality aside,
what do you mean by vibrations?

95
00:20:50,141 --> 00:20:52,496
The poetry of vibrations cannot
be described

96
00:20:52,621 --> 00:20:55,260
with the vulgarity of words.

97
00:20:55,941 --> 00:20:58,057
Well, try at least.

98
00:20:58,221 --> 00:21:00,177
l'm an artist,
l don't need to explain jack shit.

99
00:21:00,381 --> 00:21:04,897
So l'll write: "Lives on vibrations,
but she doesn't know what they are."

100
00:21:05,141 --> 00:21:07,177
l'm starting to dislike
this interview,

101
00:21:07,301 --> 00:21:09,212
l sense conflictuality in you.

102
00:21:09,381 --> 00:21:12,657
- Conflictuality as a vibration?
- As a pain in the ass.

103
00:21:12,821 --> 00:21:15,494
Let's talk about my mom's
abusive boyfriend.

104
00:21:15,701 --> 00:21:19,171
No! l want to know
what a vibration is.

105
00:21:22,341 --> 00:21:24,650
lt's my radar to intercept
the world.

106
00:21:24,821 --> 00:21:26,812
Your radar... meaning?

107
00:21:27,861 --> 00:21:29,852
You're a pain in the ass.

108
00:21:29,981 --> 00:21:31,937
We got off to a bad start...

109
00:21:32,061 --> 00:21:34,814
Talia Concept wants to be
interviewed by your paper,

110
00:21:34,941 --> 00:21:37,774
it has many readers.
But you're biased.

111
00:21:37,901 --> 00:21:41,610
Write about how she has sex
with her fiance 11 times a day,

112
00:21:41,741 --> 00:21:43,538
he's a talented conceptual artist,

113
00:21:43,661 --> 00:21:46,698
he covers basketballs with confetti!
He's sensational!

114
00:21:46,821 --> 00:21:50,018
Talia Concept is talking about
things that are meaningless to me.

115
00:21:50,141 --> 00:21:52,496
All l've heard
is unpublishable fluff.

116
00:21:52,661 --> 00:21:55,016
You can't charm me
with things like:

117
00:21:55,141 --> 00:21:57,894
"l'm an artist,
l don't need to explain".

118
00:21:58,021 --> 00:22:00,489
Our paper has a core
of cultured readers

119
00:22:00,661 --> 00:22:03,129
that don't want to be taken
for fools. l work for that core.

120
00:22:03,261 --> 00:22:05,821
So let me talk about my eventful,

121
00:22:05,981 --> 00:22:08,654
difficult but necessary
journey as an artist!

122
00:22:08,781 --> 00:22:10,419
Necessary for who?

123
00:22:10,541 --> 00:22:13,692
For heaven's sake, madam,
what is a vibration?

124
00:22:15,621 --> 00:22:18,419
- l don't know.
- You don't know.

125
00:22:18,581 --> 00:22:20,936
You are an obsessive jerk!

126
00:22:21,061 --> 00:22:24,770
l'll tell your editor to send me
a journalist of a higher stature.

127
00:22:24,901 --> 00:22:28,018
A piece of advice:
when you speak to my editor,

128
00:22:28,181 --> 00:22:31,810
go easy on the stature business.
She's a dwarf, you know.

129
00:22:33,461 --> 00:22:36,180
Jep, this interview is a hoot!

130
00:22:36,341 --> 00:22:38,377
Maybe, but don't send me

131
00:22:38,501 --> 00:22:40,253
to interview someone
who head-butts walls again.

132
00:22:41,381 --> 00:22:44,293
- You know what the trick is?
- Foam rubber.

133
00:22:44,461 --> 00:22:46,019
Amateur dramatics isn't dead.

134
00:22:46,181 --> 00:22:50,254
Did you get offended
about the stature comment?

135
00:22:50,421 --> 00:22:53,891
Don't be silly!
That's the funniest bit!

136
00:22:54,061 --> 00:22:56,211
l'm a dwarf, it's no secret.

137
00:22:56,381 --> 00:22:59,259
lt's the first and last thing
everyone says about me.

138
00:22:59,421 --> 00:23:02,777
You're a spectacular woman, Dadina.
You've had the career you deserve.

139
00:23:02,941 --> 00:23:06,297
But you haven't had the career
you deserve.

140
00:23:06,901 --> 00:23:08,892
Maybe l don't have much to say...

141
00:23:09,021 --> 00:23:12,616
Bullshit, you're lazy.
You never leave Rome.

142
00:23:12,781 --> 00:23:15,341
Go to Giglio to do that report
on the Concordia

143
00:23:15,461 --> 00:23:17,179
l've asked you to do 50 times.

144
00:23:21,581 --> 00:23:24,891
Re-heated rice is always tastier
than freshly cooked rice.

145
00:23:25,061 --> 00:23:27,370
The old is better than the new.

146
00:23:28,181 --> 00:23:29,933
Plans tonight, cherie?

147
00:23:30,101 --> 00:23:33,650
As the great De Blasi,
my predecessor, said:

148
00:23:33,821 --> 00:23:37,496
"Tonight l'll do two things,
eat soup and have a shag."

149
00:23:37,661 --> 00:23:39,970
Two things that contradict
each other.

150
00:23:40,141 --> 00:23:43,099
That's what l'd say too,
and she'd reply, in a serious tone:

151
00:23:43,261 --> 00:23:47,379
"No, Dadina, they don't,
because they're both hot."

152
00:23:49,661 --> 00:23:52,892
There's a publishing house
in Ancona, it's not that small,

153
00:23:53,101 --> 00:23:55,057
they want an interview book
about you.

154
00:23:55,181 --> 00:23:59,060
Another interview book?
We're obsessed with interviews!

155
00:23:59,181 --> 00:24:02,298
Can't you hear them?
"As l always say"... to who?

156
00:24:02,461 --> 00:24:03,860
Forget it!

157
00:24:03,981 --> 00:24:06,575
And honestly,
who'll buy a book called:

158
00:24:06,701 --> 00:24:09,773
"Visions and revisions.
Jep Gambardella's Galaxy"?

159
00:24:09,941 --> 00:24:11,693
lt's a serious title!

160
00:24:11,861 --> 00:24:14,580
Unfortunately in this country,
in order to be taken seriously,

161
00:24:14,741 --> 00:24:16,811
you have to take yourself seriously.

162
00:24:16,981 --> 00:24:21,293
l only wrote one novel, 40 years ago.
lmpossible to find too...

163
00:24:21,461 --> 00:24:24,294
Bullshit, "The Human Apparatus"
was a masterpiece!

164
00:24:24,461 --> 00:24:26,372
lt even won the... what was it?

165
00:24:26,541 --> 00:24:29,101
- The Bancarella prize.
- Shit, the Bancarella prize!

166
00:24:29,261 --> 00:24:32,571
You're very kind, but forget it...
it'd be too pompous.

167
00:24:32,701 --> 00:24:36,091
l can't, you'll put me
in an awkward position.

168
00:24:36,301 --> 00:24:39,373
l've agreed and l've even accepted
an advance...

169
00:24:39,501 --> 00:24:40,934
- How much?
- 1,500 euros.

170
00:24:41,141 --> 00:24:43,575
Give it back,
l'll give you 1,500 euros.

171
00:24:43,741 --> 00:24:46,892
By the way,
l spoke to the theatre people.

172
00:24:47,021 --> 00:24:50,093
They'll give you three nights
but you pay for the lights.

173
00:24:50,261 --> 00:24:52,013
Who cares about that!

174
00:24:52,181 --> 00:24:54,137
Jep, this is great news.

175
00:24:54,541 --> 00:24:57,214
lt's really great news.
Thank you!

176
00:25:03,141 --> 00:25:06,770
Are you still up?
lt's time to go to bed.

177
00:25:06,941 --> 00:25:08,932
That's Viola Bartoli,
Bartoli's widow.

178
00:25:09,061 --> 00:25:11,621
The guy who was killed,
the actual Bartoli.

179
00:25:11,821 --> 00:25:15,894
Viola has a 50 metre yacht
that belonged to Himmler, the Nazi.

180
00:25:16,181 --> 00:25:18,137
You know what l call Viola?

181
00:25:18,301 --> 00:25:20,815
- No, what?
- "To-good-to-poo".

182
00:25:20,981 --> 00:25:24,451
- l don't understand.
- Because she's pernickety.

183
00:25:24,581 --> 00:25:26,890
Usually pernickety people don't poo.

184
00:25:27,061 --> 00:25:30,098
When l introduced Trumeau
to my family, my father said:

185
00:25:30,221 --> 00:25:33,691
"Miss, before marrying my son,
have you ever seen him poo?"

186
00:25:33,901 --> 00:25:36,176
- How gross!
- lt's not as bad as you think.

187
00:25:36,341 --> 00:25:40,812
Actually, my wife and l are the only
couple in ltaly who are in love.

188
00:25:40,941 --> 00:25:42,897
Orietta, watch out for Lello.

189
00:25:43,061 --> 00:25:44,619
Yes, l know.

190
00:25:44,741 --> 00:25:47,539
He's the world's greatest salesman,
he cons everyone.

191
00:25:47,661 --> 00:25:49,538
ln no time he'll get you to spend
every penny

192
00:25:49,661 --> 00:25:50,776
on whatever he's selling.

193
00:25:50,941 --> 00:25:52,215
You always flatter me.

194
00:25:52,381 --> 00:25:56,010
Just because l express myself well
doesn't mean l'm always working!

195
00:25:56,141 --> 00:25:58,132
- What do you do?
- l sell toys.

196
00:25:58,301 --> 00:26:00,132
Not just in a shop,

197
00:26:00,301 --> 00:26:03,657
he's a wholesaler on a global scale,
he even sells to the Chinese!

198
00:26:03,781 --> 00:26:05,009
What about him?

199
00:26:05,181 --> 00:26:09,299
Don't you know him? Sebastiano Paf,
perhaps ltaly's greatest poet.

200
00:26:09,461 --> 00:26:14,774
He wrote: "Up with life,
down with reminiscence."

201
00:26:15,701 --> 00:26:18,454
He's on the Dukan Diet,
so Dadina won't leave him.

202
00:26:18,781 --> 00:26:19,611
ls he with her?

203
00:26:19,741 --> 00:26:22,460
- He is, but she...
- Like at high school.

204
00:26:23,541 --> 00:26:25,338
Why doesn't he ever talk?

205
00:26:25,501 --> 00:26:27,457
Because he listens.

206
00:26:29,461 --> 00:26:32,578
- Stop sniffing up with your nose?
- Bugger off.

207
00:26:32,701 --> 00:26:37,092
Jep's found a theatre for me.
Do you want the lead role?

208
00:26:37,261 --> 00:26:40,139
l'm no longer an actress,
l'm a writer now.

209
00:26:40,381 --> 00:26:42,133
Maybe...

210
00:26:42,941 --> 00:26:44,852
Maybe l'll direct a film.

211
00:26:45,021 --> 00:26:48,934
- Viola, darling!
- Help me, l'm worried about my son.

212
00:26:49,101 --> 00:26:52,013
- What can l do?
- Why don't you talk to him?

213
00:26:52,141 --> 00:26:54,530
You always say you're good
with strangers...

214
00:26:54,661 --> 00:26:56,617
That's the problem, l'm too good.

215
00:26:56,781 --> 00:27:01,013
- ls he seeing a therapist?
- Yes, but he wants to stop going.

216
00:27:01,181 --> 00:27:05,618
Take him to a psychiatrist, they're
pragmatic: Ativan, Prozac and so on.

217
00:27:05,781 --> 00:27:07,533
That stuff makes him feel worse.

218
00:27:07,701 --> 00:27:11,250
Relax, he's always been odd,
he is what he is.

219
00:27:11,381 --> 00:27:14,453
By the way, have you tried
this rascal's endive quiche?

220
00:27:14,621 --> 00:27:18,091
lt's the first time she's made it
and it's better than my mom's,

221
00:27:18,261 --> 00:27:21,571
please, you must try some!

222
00:27:26,981 --> 00:27:28,778
You changed your hair colour.

223
00:27:30,101 --> 00:27:32,774
l feel Pirandello-esque lately...

224
00:27:34,301 --> 00:27:37,134
- Great jazz, no?
- Not really.

225
00:27:37,261 --> 00:27:41,732
The Ethiopian jazz scene is the only
interesting one today.

226
00:27:41,901 --> 00:27:45,098
l'm from Milan, to be honest...
l find Romans...

227
00:27:45,621 --> 00:27:46,770
unbearable!

228
00:27:46,941 --> 00:27:49,580
The best people in Rome
are the tourists.

229
00:27:49,701 --> 00:27:51,100
Take ltaly...

230
00:27:51,261 --> 00:27:54,537
What are we famous for overseas?
Fashion and pizza.

231
00:27:54,701 --> 00:27:57,090
A country of weavers and grocers.

232
00:27:57,261 --> 00:28:01,140
How can someone who sells toys,
bringing joy to the world,

233
00:28:01,261 --> 00:28:04,378
be such a pessimist
and a defeatist? You're dark.

234
00:28:04,541 --> 00:28:06,099
- Dark?
- Yes.

235
00:28:06,261 --> 00:28:08,980
l heard Gisella Montanelli
went to loans sharks

236
00:28:09,141 --> 00:28:10,813
to pay her hairdressing debts.

237
00:28:10,981 --> 00:28:12,573
Jep says l'm dark!

238
00:28:12,741 --> 00:28:14,254
Gisella's really sunk that low?

239
00:28:14,381 --> 00:28:19,409
Rome is the only city in the world
where Marxism has truly existed.

240
00:28:19,581 --> 00:28:22,459
You can't excel over others
